netite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"black smoker-type conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on magnetite surface, undergoes deoxygenation facilitated by H\u2082 to yield CO and H\u2082O. The reaction proceeds through a surface carboxylate/carbonate intermediate that is reduced stepwise.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide minerals has been documented at hydrothermal temperatures (McCollom & Seewald, 2003; Seewald et al., 2006). CO is an essential feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and a precursor to formaldehyde and acetaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:1\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on magnetite surface and undergoes partial hydrogenation. Surface-bound formyl (HCO) intermediate is further hydrogenated to yield formaldehyde, which desorbs into the aqueous phase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde is a recognized C1 intermediate in Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on iron oxide minerals under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom et al., 1999; Holm & Hennet, 1992). While formaldehyde is typically transient, it can be stabilized by rapid reaction with nucleophiles or transport away from the catalytic surface.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Stepwise CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate via formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH, requires multi-step carbon-carbon bond formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced to formaldehyde/methanol equivalents on mineral surfaces. Sequential C-C bond forming condensations on iron-sulfur surfaces build the C3 skeleton: C1 (formate) \u2192 C2 (acetate/glycolate) \u2192 C3 (pyruvate). The \u03b1-keto acid arises from oxidative rearrangement or direct assembly of a C2 + C1 unit.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated native iron-driven CO\u2082 fixation through a series of \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate, recapitulating portions of the reductive TCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that Fe\u2070 and FeS can reduce CO\u2082 to formate, acetate, and pyruvate under mild aqueous conditions. This represents a core abiotic pathway from one-carbon feedstocks to central metabolic intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetyl-CoA pathway analog: CO/CO\u2082 to pyruvate on FeNiS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeNiS minerals (greigite analog with Ni doping)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Ni-doped iron-sulfur surfaces, alkaline conditions, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and CO\u2082 are co-reduced on Ni-doped iron-sulfide surfaces. An activated C1 unit (CO or methyl group) undergoes carbonyl insertion to form an acetyl intermediate, analogous to the biological acetyl-CoA pathway. The acetyl group is further carboxylated to yield pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) demonstrated that CO and methylthiol on FeNiS surfaces produce activated acetic acid under hydrothermal conditions \u2014 an analog of the biological acetyl-CoA pathway. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed CO\u2082 fixation on Fe-Ni minerals yielding formate, acetate, and pyruvate. Weiss et al. (2016) argued the acetyl-CoA pathway is the most ancient carbon fixation route, with greigite as its mineral analog.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS / greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083 from vent fluids, pH 8-10, H\u2082 as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks the \u03b1-keto group of pyruvate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is subsequently reduced by mineral-surface-bound hydride (from H\u2082 dissociation on FeS) to yield alanine. The reaction is analogous to biological glutamate dehydrogenase activity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) showed reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Wang et al. (2011) demonstrated alanine formation from pyruvate and ammonia on iron sulfide minerals. This represents the most direct hydrothermal route to amino acids and is considered part of the proto-metabolic network at alkaline vents (Sojo et al., 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"thermal activation, acidic to neutral pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermally driven decarboxylation at the \u03b1-keto position, losing CO\u2082 and yielding acetaldehyde. Pyrite surfaces lower the activation energy by coordinating the carboxylate groups. The reaction is analogous to non-oxidative decarboxylation in biochemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is a well-established reaction under hydrothermal conditions (Seewald, 2001; Cody et al., 2004). Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde occurs readily above 350K, and pyrite surfaces facilitate this process by stabilizing the transition state (Cooper et al., 2011). This reaction connects the \u03b1-keto acid hub to the aldehyde hub.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"C2 product of FTT synthesis, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO undergoes surface-catalyzed C-C coupling on magnetite: a surface methyl (or methylene) group from initial CO hydrogenation reacts with a second CO to form a C2 oxygenate. The surface-bound acetyl intermediate is hydrogenated and released as acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces a distribution of C1-C5 products including alcohols, aldehydes, and hydrocarbons (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). Acetaldehyde is a recognized C2 product of this chemistry. Holm & Hennet (1992) proposed FTT synthesis as a major source of organic molecules at hydrothermal vents.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 1: aminonitrile formation from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay mineral surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"weakly acidic to neutral pH, concentrated evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia condenses with acetaldehyde to form an imine (acetaldimine, CH\u2083CH=NH). HCN then adds across the C=N bond in a nucleophilic addition to yield 2-aminopropionitrile. Clay surfaces concentrate the reactants and may lower the activation energy for imine formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest and most robust routes to amino acids under prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984). Acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 2-aminopropionitrile has been demonstrated in numerous simulated prebiotic experiments. Montmorillonite clays are known to concentrate and catalyze condensation reactions (Ferris et al., 1996).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 2: hydrolysis of aminonitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, mild acidic conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"hydrolysis in warm evaporitic pool, may require days-weeks at ambient T\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of 2-aminopropionitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (-CONH\u2082) then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH), releasing NH\u2083. The net transformation is: CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)COOH + NH\u2083. Clay surfaces may catalyze the hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds at moderate temperatures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The reaction is slower than imine formation but occurs readily in warm aqueous conditions over geologically short timescales. NH\u2083 released can be recycled. Note: this produces racemic alanine; L-selectivity requires additional chiral selection mechanisms.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile (glycine precursor)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool containing formaldehyde, NH\u2083, and HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form methyleneimine (H\u2082C=NH). HCN adds across the imine to yield aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). This is the Strecker route to the simplest amino acid precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde-based Strecker synthesis to aminoacetonitrile was demonstrated in the original Miller-Urey-type experiments (Miller, 1957) and is the dominant pathway to glycine under prebiotic conditions. Formaldehyde is a ubiquitous prebiotic C1 source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"warm aqueous pool, weakly acidic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminoacetonitrile undergoes hydrolysis of the nitrile group: H\u2082NCH\u2082CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH + NH\u2083, proceeding through the amide intermediate glycinamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Glycine is the most abundant amino acid in meteorites and prebiotic simulation experiments, consistent with this pathway being kinetically favorable.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of pyruvate by glycine to form alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"metal ion catalysis (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a) or pyridoxal analog\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pool, metal ion cofactors present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycine forms a Schiff base with a pyridoxal or metal ion cofactor, which tautomerizes to a ketimine. Hydrolysis releases glyoxylate. The liberated amino group is transferred to pyruvate via the reverse process to yield alanine. Net: pyruvate + glycine \u2192 alanine + glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination between \u03b1-keto acids and amino acids is one of the most fundamental metabolic reactions. W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1990) proposed that prebiotic transamination on mineral surfaces could interconvert amino acids and keto acids. Metzler et al. (1954) showed non-enzymatic transamination with metal ion catalysts. This pathway connects the glycine and pyruvate branches of the network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Condensation of formate and ammonia to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling required for dehydration condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"During the drying phase of wet-dry cycles, formate and ammonia are concentrated on clay surfaces. Thermal dehydration drives condensation to form formamide (HCONH\u2082). Clay interlayer spaces provide a confined micro-environment favoring the reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a key prebiotic molecule that can be formed from thermal dehydration of ammonium formate (Saladino et al., 2012). Bada et al. (2007) discussed the prebiotic relevance of formamide as a precursor to nucleobases and HCN. Wet-dry cycling on mineral surfaces provides the thermodynamic driving force for this dehydration reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), no ozone shielding on early Earth\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photons (absorbed directly by formamide or via TiO\u2082 photocatalysis) induce N-H and C-H bond homolysis. Subsequent radical recombination and dehydration produce HCN and H\u2082O. TiO\u2082 surfaces generate reactive radical species that enhance the photodegradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"UV photodecomposition of formamide to HCN has been demonstrated experimentally (Barks et al., 2010; Saladino et al., 2012). TiO\u2082 (anatase) is a common mineral photocatalyst on the early Earth surface that enhances formamide photochemistry (Saladino et al., 2013). The intense UV flux on the prebiotic Earth (no ozone layer) makes this a robust source of HCN from formamide.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of pyruvate to lactate on FeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto group of pyruvate is reduced by surface-bound hydride (from H\u2082 dissociation on FeS) to yield the \u03b1-hydroxy acid lactate. This is a simple two-electron reduction analogous to biological lactate dehydrogenase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FeS-mediated reduction of \u03b1-keto acids to \u03b1-hydroxy acids has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska et al., 2017; Varma et al., 2018). Lactate was identified as a product of pyruvate reduction on native iron and iron sulfide surfaces. This provides an alternative branch from pyruvate to alanine via lactate amination.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of lactate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay minerals, mild acidic or neutral pH\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling to drive dehydration, concentrated NH\u2083\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under concentrated conditions during drying, the hydroxyl group of lactate is displaced by ammonia via an SN2-type mechanism or through an intermediate \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated acid formed by dehydration, followed by ammonia addition. The reaction is kinetically slow but thermodynamically accessible under dehydrating conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Amination of \u03b1-hydroxy acids to \u03b1-amino acids has been proposed as an alternative prebiotic route (Weber, 2001; Bada, 2013). While less efficient than reductive amination or Strecker synthesis, this pathway is plausible under concentrating/dehydrating surface conditions. It represents a surface-environment alternative using a hydrothermal intermediate (lactate).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate-pyruvate reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, formate undergoes further CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate, and pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine \u2014 all within the hydrothermal vent environment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetyl-CoA analog pathway to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is converted to CO via reverse water-gas shift, then CO and CO\u2082 are combined on FeNiS surfaces to produce pyruvate directly via an acetyl-CoA pathway analog, followed by reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch acetaldehyde to alanine via Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to CO, then Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite yields acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis with NH\u2083 and HCN produces aminopropionitrile, hydrolyzed to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde + Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is fixed to formate then pyruvate in the hydrothermal environment. Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, which enters the surface Strecker pathway to produce alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"CO-route pyruvate decarboxylation + Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is converted to CO, pyruvate is made via the acetyl-CoA analog route, decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, then Strecker synthesis on the surface yields alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-pyruvate-lactate-amination pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate is made hydrothermally, converted to pyruvate, reduced to lactate on FeS, then transported to surface pools where amination with NH\u2083 yields alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"CO-route pyruvate-lactate-amination pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is produced via the CO/CO\u2082 acetyl-CoA analog pathway, reduced to lactate, then aminated on the surface to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination: glycine donates amino group to pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is made hydrothermally (via formate route). Independently, formaldehyde from FTT synthesis is used in surface Strecker synthesis to produce glycine. Glycine and pyruvate converge in transamination to produce alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-HCN-Strecker pathway via FTT acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate is transported to the surface and condensed with NH\u2083 to formamide under wet-dry conditions. UV photolysis of formamide on TiO\u2082 produces HCN. Simultaneously, acetaldehyde from FTT synthesis is available. HCN + acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 undergo Strecker synthesis to yield alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-HCN + FTT formaldehyde \u2192 glycine \u2192 transamination\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is produced from formamide photolysis (formamide from formate + NH\u2083). Formaldehyde from FTT synthesis combines with NH\u2083 and HCN via Strecker to produce glycine. Glycine then donates its amino group to hydrothermally-produced pyruvate via transamination to yield alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the central metabolic hub: formed by at least two independent hydrothermal routes, it feeds into reductive amination, decarboxylation, reduction, and transamination.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde bridges hydrothermal and surface chemistry: formed by FTT synthesis or pyruvate decarboxylation, it is the key substrate for Strecker amino acid synthesis.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is the essential nitrogen-carbon coupling agent for Strecker synthesis. It can be derived from formamide UV photolysis or from atmospheric/volcanic sources.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate is the first stable reduction product of CO\u2082 and feeds into pyruvate synthesis, formamide formation, and serves as a one-carbon donor.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Alanine", "overall_strategy": "L-Alanine is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network originating from CO\u2082, H\u2082, NH\u2083, and HCN. Four major hub molecules \u2014 pyruvate, acetaldehyde, formate, and HCN \u2014 channel carbon and nitrogen from hydrothermal vent chemistry (CO\u2082 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals, Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis) into surface chemistry (Strecker synthesis, wet-dry dehydration) and biochemical assembly (transamination, reductive amination). Ten distinct pathways connect simple C1 gases to L-alanine via reductive amination of pyruvate, Strecker synthesis through acetaldehyde, transamination with glycine, and amination of lactate. The network emphasizes redundancy: pyruvate itself is accessible from at least three independent hydrothermal routes, and the Strecker branch operates independently on the surface using HCN derived from multiple sources.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropionitrile", "common_name": "2-aminopropionitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2H,4H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "L-Alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)/t2-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "lactic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2,4H,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoethanoic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 binds to the surface of greigite, which is structurally analogous to the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] cluster in carbon monoxide dehydrogenase. Hydride transfer from dissociatively adsorbed H\u2082 reduces CO\u2082 to formate via a surface-bound carboxyl intermediate.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally under mild hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). This reaction is the entry point for one-carbon fixation at alkaline hydrothermal vents and is considered the first step of an abiotic acetyl-CoA pathway analog (Russell & Martin, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "black smoker-type conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on magnetite surface, undergoes deoxygenation facilitated by H\u2082 to yield CO and H\u2082O. The reaction proceeds through a surface carboxylate/carbonate intermediate that is reduced stepwise.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide minerals has been documented at hydrothermal temperatures (McCollom & Seewald, 2003; Seewald et al., 2006). CO is an essential feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and a precursor to formaldehyde and acetaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:1"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on magnetite surface and undergoes partial hydrogenation. Surface-bound formyl (HCO) intermediate is further hydrogenated to yield formaldehyde, which desorbs into the aqueous phase.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde is a recognized C1 intermediate in Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on iron oxide minerals under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom et al., 1999; Holm & Hennet, 1992). While formaldehyde is typically transient, it can be stabilized by rapid reaction with nucleophiles or transport away from the catalytic surface."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Stepwise CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate via formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pH, requires multi-step carbon-carbon bond formation"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced to formaldehyde/methanol equivalents on mineral surfaces. Sequential C-C bond forming condensations on iron-sulfur surfaces build the C3 skeleton: C1 (formate) \u2192 C2 (acetate/glycolate) \u2192 C3 (pyruvate). The \u03b1-keto acid arises from oxidative rearrangement or direct assembly of a C2 + C1 unit.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated native iron-driven CO\u2082 fixation through a series of \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate, recapitulating portions of the reductive TCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that Fe\u2070 and FeS can reduce CO\u2082 to formate, acetate, and pyruvate under mild aqueous conditions. This represents a core abiotic pathway from one-carbon feedstocks to central metabolic intermediates."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Acetyl-CoA pathway analog: CO/CO\u2082 to pyruvate on FeNiS", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "FeNiS minerals (greigite analog with Ni doping)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Ni-doped iron-sulfur surfaces, alkaline conditions, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "CO and CO\u2082 are co-reduced on Ni-doped iron-sulfide surfaces. An activated C1 unit (CO or methyl group) undergoes carbonyl insertion to form an acetyl intermediate, analogous to the biological acetyl-CoA pathway. The acetyl group is further carboxylated to yield pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) demonstrated that CO and methylthiol on FeNiS surfaces produce activated acetic acid under hydrothermal conditions \u2014 an analog of the biological acetyl-CoA pathway. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed CO\u2082 fixation on Fe-Ni minerals yielding formate, acetate, and pyruvate. Weiss et al. (2016) argued the acetyl-CoA pathway is the most ancient carbon fixation route, with greigite as its mineral analog."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS / greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH\u2083 from vent fluids, pH 8-10, H\u2082 as reductant"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the \u03b1-keto group of pyruvate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is subsequently reduced by mineral-surface-bound hydride (from H\u2082 dissociation on FeS) to yield alanine. The reaction is analogous to biological glutamate dehydrogenase activity.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) showed reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Wang et al. (2011) demonstrated alanine formation from pyruvate and ammonia on iron sulfide minerals. This represents the most direct hydrothermal route to amino acids and is considered part of the proto-metabolic network at alkaline vents (Sojo et al., 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "thermal activation, acidic to neutral pH"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermally driven decarboxylation at the \u03b1-keto position, losing CO\u2082 and yielding acetaldehyde. Pyrite surfaces lower the activation energy by coordinating the carboxylate groups. The reaction is analogous to non-oxidative decarboxylation in biochemistry.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is a well-established reaction under hydrothermal conditions (Seewald, 2001; Cody et al., 2004). Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde occurs readily above 350K, and pyrite surfaces facilitate this process by stabilizing the transition state (Cooper et al., 2011). This reaction connects the \u03b1-keto acid hub to the aldehyde hub."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "C2 product of FTT synthesis, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:2"}, "mechanism": "CO undergoes surface-catalyzed C-C coupling on magnetite: a surface methyl (or methylene) group from initial CO hydrogenation reacts with a second CO to form a C2 oxygenate. The surface-bound acetyl intermediate is hydrogenated and released as acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces a distribution of C1-C5 products including alcohols, aldehydes, and hydrocarbons (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). Acetaldehyde is a recognized C2 product of this chemistry. Holm & Hennet (1992) proposed FTT synthesis as a major source of organic molecules at hydrothermal vents."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 1: aminonitrile formation from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay mineral surface)", "aqueous": true, "other": "weakly acidic to neutral pH, concentrated evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia condenses with acetaldehyde to form an imine (acetaldimine, CH\u2083CH=NH). HCN then adds across the C=N bond in a nucleophilic addition to yield 2-aminopropionitrile. Clay surfaces concentrate the reactants and may lower the activation energy for imine formation.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest and most robust routes to amino acids under prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984). Acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 2-aminopropionitrile has been demonstrated in numerous simulated prebiotic experiments. Montmorillonite clays are known to concentrate and catalyze condensation reactions (Ferris et al., 1996)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 2: hydrolysis of aminonitrile to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, mild acidic conditions", "aqueous": true, "other": "hydrolysis in warm evaporitic pool, may require days-weeks at ambient T"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of 2-aminopropionitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (-CONH\u2082) then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH), releasing NH\u2083. The net transformation is: CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)COOH + NH\u2083. Clay surfaces may catalyze the hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Strecker aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds at moderate temperatures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The reaction is slower than imine formation but occurs readily in warm aqueous conditions over geologically short timescales. NH\u2083 released can be recycled. Note: this produces racemic alanine; L-selectivity requires additional chiral selection mechanisms."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile (glycine precursor)", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "concentrated pool containing formaldehyde, NH\u2083, and HCN"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form methyleneimine (H\u2082C=NH). HCN adds across the imine to yield aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). This is the Strecker route to the simplest amino acid precursor.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde-based Strecker synthesis to aminoacetonitrile was demonstrated in the original Miller-Urey-type experiments (Miller, 1957) and is the dominant pathway to glycine under prebiotic conditions. Formaldehyde is a ubiquitous prebiotic C1 source."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "warm aqueous pool, weakly acidic"}, "mechanism": "Aminoacetonitrile undergoes hydrolysis of the nitrile group: H\u2082NCH\u2082CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH + NH\u2083, proceeding through the amide intermediate glycinamide.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Glycine is the most abundant amino acid in meteorites and prebiotic simulation experiments, consistent with this pathway being kinetically favorable."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Transamination of pyruvate by glycine to form alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "metal ion catalysis (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a) or pyridoxal analog", "aqueous": true, "other": "concentrated prebiotic pool, metal ion cofactors present"}, "mechanism": "Glycine forms a Schiff base with a pyridoxal or metal ion cofactor, which tautomerizes to a ketimine. Hydrolysis releases glyoxylate. The liberated amino group is transferred to pyruvate via the reverse process to yield alanine. Net: pyruvate + glycine \u2192 alanine + glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Transamination between \u03b1-keto acids and amino acids is one of the most fundamental metabolic reactions. W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1990) proposed that prebiotic transamination on mineral surfaces could interconvert amino acids and keto acids. Metzler et al. (1954) showed non-enzymatic transamination with metal ion catalysts. This pathway connects the glycine and pyruvate branches of the network."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Condensation of formate and ammonia to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay, phosphate minerals", "aqueous": false, "other": "wet-dry cycling required for dehydration condensation"}, "mechanism": "During the drying phase of wet-dry cycles, formate and ammonia are concentrated on clay surfaces. Thermal dehydration drives condensation to form formamide (HCONH\u2082). Clay interlayer spaces provide a confined micro-environment favoring the reaction.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a key prebiotic molecule that can be formed from thermal dehydration of ammonium formate (Saladino et al., 2012). Bada et al. (2007) discussed the prebiotic relevance of formamide as a precursor to nucleobases and HCN. Wet-dry cycling on mineral surfaces provides the thermodynamic driving force for this dehydration reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "UV photolysis of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": false, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), no ozone shielding on early Earth"}, "mechanism": "UV photons (absorbed directly by formamide or via TiO\u2082 photocatalysis) induce N-H and C-H bond homolysis. Subsequent radical recombination and dehydration produce HCN and H\u2082O. TiO\u2082 surfaces generate reactive radical species that enhance the photodegradation.", "reasoning": "UV photodecomposition of formamide to HCN has been demonstrated experimentally (Barks et al., 2010; Saladino et al., 2012). TiO\u2082 (anatase) is a common mineral photocatalyst on the early Earth surface that enhances formamide photochemistry (Saladino et al., 2013). The intense UV flux on the prebiotic Earth (no ozone layer) makes this a robust source of HCN from formamide."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Reduction of pyruvate to lactate on FeS", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluids"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-keto group of pyruvate is reduced by surface-bound hydride (from H\u2082 dissociation on FeS) to yield the \u03b1-hydroxy acid lactate. This is a simple two-electron reduction analogous to biological lactate dehydrogenase.", "reasoning": "FeS-mediated reduction of \u03b1-keto acids to \u03b1-hydroxy acids has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska et al., 2017; Varma et al., 2018). Lactate was identified as a product of pyruvate reduction on native iron and iron sulfide surfaces. This provides an alternative branch from pyruvate to alanine via lactate amination."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Amination of lactate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay minerals, mild acidic or neutral pH", "aqueous": true, "other": "wet-dry cycling to drive dehydration, concentrated NH\u2083"}, "mechanism": "Under concentrated conditions during drying, the hydroxyl group of lactate is displaced by ammonia via an SN2-type mechanism or through an intermediate \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated acid formed by dehydration, followed by ammonia addition. The reaction is kinetically slow but thermodynamically accessible under dehydrating conditions.", "reasoning": "Amination of \u03b1-hydroxy acids to \u03b1-amino acids has been proposed as an alternative prebiotic route (Weber, 2001; Bada, 2013). While less efficient than reductive amination or Strecker synthesis, this pathway is plausible under concentrating/dehydrating surface conditions. It represents a surface-environment alternative using a hydrothermal intermediate (lactate)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal formate-pyruvate reductive amination", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, formate undergoes further CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate, and pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine \u2014 all within the hydrothermal vent environment.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal acetyl-CoA analog pathway to alanine", "description": "CO\u2082 is converted to CO via reverse water-gas shift, then CO and CO\u2082 are combined on FeNiS surfaces to produce pyruvate directly via an acetyl-CoA pathway analog, followed by reductive amination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch acetaldehyde to alanine via Strecker", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to CO, then Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite yields acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis with NH\u2083 and HCN produces aminopropionitrile, hydrolyzed to alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde + Strecker", "description": "CO\u2082 is fixed to formate then pyruvate in the hydrothermal environment. Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, which enters the surface Strecker pathway to produce alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "CO-route pyruvate decarboxylation + Strecker", "description": "CO\u2082 is converted to CO, pyruvate is made via the acetyl-CoA analog route, decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, then Strecker synthesis on the surface yields alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formate-pyruvate-lactate-amination pathway", "description": "Formate is made hydrothermally, converted to pyruvate, reduced to lactate on FeS, then transported to surface pools where amination with NH\u2083 yields alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_016", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediat