 of HCN, which is a significant strength for network self-sufficiency.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify mineral catalyst for formate-ammonia condensation\", \"Consider TiO\u2082 or other photocatalyst for the formamide route\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_006\": 0.85, \"rxn_015\": 0.80, \"rxn_013\": 0.88, \"rxn_014\": 0.75},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"The only pathway spanning all three environments: hydrothermal (pyruvate + formaldehyde generation) \u2192 surface (glycine Strecker) \u2192 biochemical (transamination). This is conceptually important for modeling the transition to proto-biochemistry. Transamination (rxn_014) requires metal ion catalysts (e.g., Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a/\u00b3\u207a) or a pyridoxal analog, which should be specified. The environmental progression is the best in the network.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify metal ion or cofactor analog catalyst for transamination\", \"Note that prebiotic transamination has been demonstrated with Cu\u00b2\u207a or pyridoxamine analogs\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.88, \"rxn_002\": 0.90, \"rxn_003\": 0.85, \"rxn_004\": 0.65, \"rxn_007\": 0.90, \"rxn_010\": 0.70, \"rxn_011\": 0.90, \"rxn_008\": 0.90, \"rxn_009\": 0.80},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\":